   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.5954_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <!-- unknown hand, could be Hardy's but might not be. Needs to be checked i.e. by Helen Gibson -->
               <note hand="other" rend="pencil" style="transform:rotateZ(90deg)">Mrs Woolf (Daughter
                  of Leslie Stephen)</note>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>TELEPHONE 496 RICHMOND.</addrLine>
               </address>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>17 The Green,</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Richmond.</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1915-01-17">17<hi rend="superscript">th.</hi> Jan.1915</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>Dear M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> Hardy,</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>I have long wished to tell you how profoundly grateful I am to you for your poems
               &amp; novels, but naturally it seemed an impertinence to do so. When however, your
               poem to my father, <persName ref="#ps:LeslieStephen">Leslie Stephen</persName>,
               appeared in <hi rend="underline"><ref target="#bib:Hardy1914_SatiresOfCircumstance"
                     >Satires of Circumstance</ref></hi> this autumn, I felt that I might perhaps be
               allowed to thank you for that at least. That poem, &amp; the reminiscences you
               contributed to <persName ref="#ps:FrederickWilliamMaitland">Professor
                  Maitland</persName>s Life of him, remain in my mind as incomparably the truest
               &amp; most imaginative portrait of him in existence, for which alone his children
               should be always grateful to you.</p>

            <p>But besides this one would like to <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.5954_2.jpg"/> thank you
               for the magnificent work which you have already done, &amp; are still to do. The
               younger generation, who care for poetry &amp; literature, owe you an immeasurable
               debt, &amp; in particular for your last volume of poems which, to me at any rate, is
               the most remarkable book to appear in my life time.</p>

            <p>I write only to satisfy a very old desire, &amp; not to trouble you to reply.</p>

            <closer>
               <salute>Believe me</salute>
               <salute>yours sincerely</salute>
               <signed>Virginia Woolf</signed>

            </closer>
            <!-- Have we decided now that the pencil mark H.5954 at top of page 2 will not be transcribed now?-->


